First off, GOOG falls outside my circle of competence. I’ve spent 60-plus years investing in simple, predictable businesses—retailing, insurance, consumer products—and I don’t pretend to fully grasp the inner workings of complex ad auctions and search-engine algorithms. With the data you’ve provided—scores of zero across fundamentals, moat, pricing power and valuation—I have no concrete footing to assess its competitive advantage or margin of safety. 

On the surface, Google benefits from scale, network effects and brand strength that suggest a moat, and its management under Sundar Pichai has generally behaved in shareholders’ interests. Its balance sheet is historically strong, with mountains of cash and modest debt. Yet without numbers on revenue consistency, return on capital or intrinsic value, I can’t tell if I’m paying a fair price. 

Long term, digital advertising will have a role, but regulatory and privacy headwinds could erode returns. Compared to businesses like Apple—where I understand the ecosystem and switching costs—or Coca-Cola—with its decades-old moat and predictable cash flow—GOOG sits in a realm of too much uncertainty for me. 

My favorite holding period is forever, but only if I know the business and have a margin of safety. In this case, I pass. I’m neither bullish nor bearish; I’m simply no better off than when I started.
